</td><td valign=top background=http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/images/bar.jpg class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uaaronagassi.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aaron Agassi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/13/02 12:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=45.topic&index=41>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.usabr.com/brainstorm/Aaron.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Why Tomorrows World Needs Nuclear Energy.</span><hr size=1> Nuclear reactors began as dangerous experiments, &quot;twisting the dragons tail&quot; to come as close to critical mass as possible. Then, for nuclear power, they simply enlarged the specs! <br>
<br>
Further more, while French reactors are more reliable and cost effective because they are made using interchangeable parts, American reactors are all custom jobs, often poorly designed in many ways and built by construction companies that take their pay and then leave the town holding the bag when nuclear power turns out to be more costly, rather than money saving. <br>
<br>
In the mean time, however, there have been safer and more efficient designs for years that do not even feature control rods and could never reach melt down if one tried. Indeed, as a test they simply switched off the cooling system and took tea and scones! <br>
<br>
The societal problems are far clearer than any purely technological issues. <br>
<br>
What we need is a Nuclear Regulatory Commission that will not become simply the interest group for the industry. We do not need pro-nuke nor anti-nuke but standards of efficiency, safety, profitability that any facility must meet, or else not be built at all until if ever they do. <br>
<br>
And perhaps we should consider the feasibility of conversion of conventional reactors to newer and better designs. That might be sellable. <br>
<br>
